defaultIntroductiondefault default&#xa0;
defaultMencap’s vision is for a truly inclusive society, where people with a learning disability 
defaultare valued equally, and get the support they need to live fulfilling lives.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultWe welcome the International Development Committee’s inquiry into Disability and Development, with a focus on ensuring disabled people are included in international development p
defaultrogrammes.
defaultThis submission focuses on the important principles which underpin inclusive education and inclusive employment practice.
default Many of these principles will underpin inclusive practice in relation to other areas of people’s lives as well. We hope a sha
defaultred understanding of these prin
defaultc
defaulti
defaultples will 
defaulthelp 
defaultensure that people with a learning disability are fully included in development pr
defaultogrammes.
default&#xa0;
defaultInclusive education practicedefaultMencap believe that children and young people with a learning disability should be educated within their local communities alongside their brothers, sisters, friends and neighbours where they are enabled to reach their full potential. 
defaultChildren with a lear
defaultning disability should attend a school in their local community that:
defaultWe supp
defaultort the policy of progressive realisation set out in the UN Convention. This recognises the importance of moving towards a system of mainstream educational provision which can provide for all disabled children, and which enables them to succeed in all area
defaults of school life. Mencap recognises that for some children, because of the nature of their support needs, there will always be the need for specialist support, but believes that this can be developed in a range of settings that facilitate inclusion and eng
defaultagement within the local community. 
defaultThese include:
defaultMencap’s aspirations for the inclusion of children with a learning disability 
defaultwithin mainstream school settings is based on the belief that there must be robust alternatives to the way that special educational needs are currently provided for in segregated settings before parents could feel confident for their children to be educate
defaultd in inclusive settings as above.
default&#xa0;
defaultMencap believes that for children with learning disabilities to be able to grow up in a world that includes them in all areas of society, they must have equal opportunities to engage with their peers from all backgrounds,
default be equipped with personal skills to progress and have presence as a valued member in the community.
